summary.seg: This copy of Peter Lombard's Glossa super Psalmos was written in the late 12th or early 13th century by an unknown yet “very fine hand". The Psalm verses are written in larger script, with various commentaries surrounding them.

Lombard (c1100- c1160) was one of the most widely-read medieval theological writers. Having studied in Paris he went on to become a teacher there, writing his Sentences, Commentary on the Pauline Epistles, and Commentary on the Psalms. This manuscript originally had large decorative initials, but these have been removed.

msItem.title: Glossa super Psalmos
Peter Lombard on the Psalms
msItem.author: Peter Lombard, Bishop of Paris, approximately 1100-1160

collation.p: 18 (wants 2,3,4,6?) 28 38 412 (wants 3) 58-98 (3 quires gone) 108 (wants 1,4,5) 118 (quires gone)128-168(quires gone) 178188(wants most of 7; quires gone)198, quires lost after ff. 71, 123, 139.

layout.p: Double columns (text and gloss) of 46 lines

handNote.p: Written in Gothic script by a single scribe.

decoNote.p: Alternate blue and red penwork initials throughout the text. Larger blue and red flourished initials indicate the major divisions of the Psalter. The first Psalm in each Nocturne (and also Ps. li (probably) and ci) had pictured initials which have been cut out.
